                <head>107. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On March 3, the President of the Commission of the <gloss target="#t_EEC1"
                        >EEC</gloss>, <persName corresp="#p_HW1">Walter Hallstein</persName>,
                    unveiled a new series of proposals for acceleration of the customs union
                    provisions of the <gloss target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss> treaty. Included were
                    proposals for the elimination of quotas on trade with non-<gloss
                        target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss> states by the end of 1961, reduction of tariffs
                    on intra-community trading by 50 percent by December 31, 1961, and the reduction
                    of the <gloss target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss> common external tariff by 20 percent
                    on July 1, 1960. For text of these proposals, see <gloss target="#t_EEC1"
                        >EEC</gloss>, Commission, <hi rend="italic">Recommendations de la Commission
                        en vue de l’ Acceleration du Rythme du Traité</hi> (Brussels, 1960). The
                        <gloss target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss> proposals were made without
                    consultations with the member states. The U.S. Government endorsed the <gloss
                        target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss> proposals in a Department of State press
                    release of March 4.</p>
            </div>
